The Economy of Violence
COPENHAGEN – What is the greatest source of violence in our world?
Brutal conflicts in Syria, in Ukraine, and elsewhere are constantly in the news, and therefore many would likely say war.
However, this turns out to be a great mistake.
The correct answer matters if we want to find cost-effective solutions for this and other global problems.
It is obvious that everyone would like to end every war and violence just as we would like to end poverty, hunger, and climate change and ensure access to education for all people.
However, given limited resources, there are limits to what the international community can do.
We must set priorities and for that an economic cost-benefit analysis can be employed.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years, and the Copenhagen Consensus has asked some of the world's leading economists to evaluate which goals, in their view, would be the smartest.
Is the goal worth the effort to reduce violence if the funds otherwise, for example, would be used to combat hunger?
And, if so, which forms of violence should be targeted?
According to a study by James Fearon from Stanford University and Anke Höffler from the Center for the Study of African Economies at Oxford University, violence in society—murders and especially violence against women and children—poses a much greater problem than civil wars.
For every death on the battlefield of a civil war, nine people die due to interpersonal violence, and for every two fighters who perish, one child is killed.
In 2008, 418,000 people were killed worldwide, and far too many countries record murder rates of over 10 victims per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization characterizes as an epidemic.
A single murder in America costs one person and society 9.1 million US dollars.
Measured against global GDP, this form of violence alone costs 1.7%.
Of course, this does not represent a direct financial loss for the world economy, but rather a way to express the consequences.
If murders could be abolished, societies around the world would be in a state that could be quantified at 1.7% of GDP.
Let us compare this with the much lower costs of civil wars, which amount to roughly 0.2% of global GDP.
This is, however, still much less than the greatest source of violence overall: domestic violence against women.
Based on studies published in the scientific journal Science, 28% of all women in sub-Saharan Africa experienced violence from their partners or family members in the past year.
These include women who were beaten, forcibly married at a young age, subjected to sexual violence, victims of crimes in the name of "honour," and circumcised.
According to a cautious estimate, the societal costs of violence by partners alone amount to 4.4 trillion US dollars or 5.2% of global GDP.
The second-largest source of violence is child abuse, which is committed by parents in 80% of cases.
The definition of child abuse varies from culture to culture, but roughly 15% of children experience what the UN characterizes as severe physical corporal punishment each month.
These include slaps in the face, head, or ears, and a quarter of these children are struck repeatedly and as forcefully as possible with an object.
This suffering affects approximately 290 million children every month.
The social costs amount to 3.6 trillion US dollars or 4.2% of global GDP.
A tiny fraction of international aid funds currently flows into reducing violence in society and improving criminal justice systems.
The enormous costs borne by society and individuals cry out for action to be taken.
Unfortunately, there are still very few reliable insights into where the limited resources should be best allocated.
All that can be said is that the money spent on reducing violence could be targeted more effectively.
Large sums of aid funds are designated for "fragile states" to help end or prevent civil wars, yet only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects with the "Crime Prevention" component.
And other programs may contribute indirectly, but clearly much could be improved.
Some solutions, it is clear, work very well.
More effective social institutions can reduce violence against children.
Studies in the US state of Washington have shown that home visits by trained professionals can reduce child abuse, improve children's quality of life, enhance their physical and mental health, and lower the costs of welfare and proceedings.
A dollar spent on this program yields a benefit of 14 US dollars: thus, it is an extremely cost-effective measure.
In many cases, societal attitudes must change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program named SASA! is implemented in Uganda.
(Turkish for "Now!") thereby spreading the notion that violence in partnerships is unacceptable and has contributed to halving the number of cases.
This is a fantastic result, even though no analysis of cost-effectiveness is available.
There are examples from other countries where effective measures have been taken.
In 1993, there were 80 murders per 100,000 inhabitants in Bogotá.
With a comprehensive approach—limiting alcohol sales time, reclaiming public spaces, and improvements in the police and justice system—the murder rate was reduced to 21 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in 2004.
This is still a high number, but far below the murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in Detroit.
Alcohol plays a role in many violent attacks, and the insights from Bogotá suggest that controlling its availability could be of crucial importance.
A pilot study in the United Kingdom showed that violent attacks could be reduced in a highly cost-efficient manner, with benefits outweighing costs by a ratio of 17 to 1.
We know still not enough, but two points are certain: Firstly, domestic violence against women and children entails annual societal costs of 8 billion US dollars and thus represents a huge – and much too neglected – global problem.
Secondly, there are solutions that can address some of these problems in a highly cost-effective manner.
Therefore, reducing domestic violence belongs to the narrower selection of the next development goals of the world.
